1 AN ACT concerning income taxation; relating to credits; providing for the
2 preceptor income tax incentive act; establishing a credit for nursing
3 home administrators, registered nurses and registered dietitians that
4 serve as community-based faculty preceptor in adult care homes and
5 medical care facilities by providing personalized instruction, training
6 and supervision for students.
7
8 WHEREAS, There are persistent obstacles in overcoming barriers to
9 professional instruction, training and supervision that are necessary for
10 aging services and healthcare services to obtain the requisite professional
11 mentoring and supervision and thereby allow them to practice upon
12 obtaining their degree or certification; and
13 WHEREAS, The tax credit is to provide sufficient financial incentives
14 that would encourage preceptors to offer professional instruction, training
15 and supervision to students matriculating at postsecondary educational
16 institutions or sponsored program and seeking careers as nursing home
17 administrators, registered nurses and or certified dietary managers in this
18 state.
19 Now, therefore:
20 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the State of Kansas:
21 Section 1. (a) The provisions of this section shall be known and may
22 be cited as the preceptor income tax incentive act.
23 (b) For taxable year years 2025, and all tax years thereafter through
24 2029, there shall be allowed a credit against the tax liability imposed under
25 the Kansas income tax act for a community-based faculty preceptor if such
26 taxpayer conducts a preceptorship for a student. The amount of credit shall
27 be based on a completed hourly total that the preceptor has provided to a
28 student teaching during each tax year. Every completed 40 hours
29 precepting provided to a student shall entitle the preceptor to a $250 tax
30 credit. A community-based faculty preceptor may accrue tax credits
31 without limitation based on the number of completed 40 hours that the
32 preceptor completes during the tax year. A preceptor shall not accrue credit
33 if such preceptor or such preceptor's employer is compensated by another
34 organization for the same preceptorship.
35 (c) Every preceptor claiming a tax credit under this section shall

